{{Infobox Person | name = Isaac Dudley Fletcher | image = Isaac D. Fletcher MET DP339744.jpg |caption = Portrait by Carnig Eksergian | birth_date = 1844 | death_date = 28 April 1917 | nationality = American | spouse =Marie Elizabeth Pickering<ref>{{cite web|url=http://research.frick.org/directoryweb/browserecord.php?-action=browse&-recid=7443|title=Archives Directory for the History of Collecting|website=Research.frick.org|accessdate=28 August 2017}}</ref> }} '''Isaac Dudley Fletcher''' (1844 – 1917) was a US businessman, art collector and museum benefactor.
He had the mansion built that is called today the [[Harry F. Sinclair House]]. He was president of Barrett Manufacturing Company and acquired a large art collection which he bequeathed to the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]].<ref name=MET>{{cite web|url=http://www.metmuseum.org/pubs/bulletins/1/pdf/3253700.pdf.bannered.pdf|format=PDF|title=1918 museum bulletin describing the bequeathed collection|website=Metmuseum.org|accessdate=2017-08-28}}</ref>
According to the Frick library, he owned work by "David, Gainsborough, Rembrandt, Reynolds, and Rubens, Alexander H Wyant, Corot and Daubigny".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://research.frick.org/directoryweb/browserecord.php?-action=browse&-recid=7443|title=Fletcher, Isaac Dudley, 1844-1917|website=Research.frick.org|accessdate=2017-08-28}}</ref> The "work by David" referred to the ''[[Portrait of Charlotte du Val d'Ognes (Marie-Denise Villers)|Portrait of Charlotte du Val d'Ognes]]'', which at the time of the bequest in 1917 was still attributed to Jacques-Louis David, but since 1995 has been attributed to [[Marie-Denise Villers]].
Besides the collection itself, the bequest included a large sum of money to start a fund for the purchase of art. According to the 1994 Museum guidebook, several of the paintings listed were purchased through the ''Fletcher Fund'', most notably the ''[[Portrait of Juan de Pareja]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.nl/books?id=zoM2KmG_ndgC&pg=PA169|title=The Metropolitan Museum of Art Guide|first1=Philippe De|last1=Montebello|date=28 August 1994|publisher=Metropolitan Museum of Art|accessdate=28 August 2017|via=Google Books}}</ref>
